abstract.1: serbia<Serbia> (/ˈsɜːrbiə/, serbian:<Serbian_language> србија / srbija, ipa: [sř̩bija]), officially the republic of serbia<Republic_of_Serbia> (serbian:<Serbian_language> република србија / republika srbija), is a sovereign state<Serbia> situated at the crossroads between central and southeast europe, covering the southern part of the pannonian plain and the central balkans
abstract.3: serbia<Serbia> is landlocked and borders hungary to the north; romania and bulgaria to the east; macedonia<Kingdom_of_Serbia> to the south; and croatia, bosnia-herzegovina, and montenegro to the west; it also claims a border with albania through the disputed territory of kosovo<Serbia>
abstract.4: serbia<Serbia> numbers around 7 million residents, and its capital<Belgrade>, belgrade<Belgrade>, ranks among the largest cities in southeast europe
abstract.6: the serbian kingdom<Kingdom_of_Serbia_(medieval)> obtained recognition by rome and the byzantine empire<Serbian_Empire> in 1217; it reached its peak in 1346 as a relatively short-lived serbian empire<Serbian_Empire>
abstract.7: by the mid-16th century, the entire modern-day serbia<Serbia> was annexed by the ottomans, at times interrupted by the habsburg empire<Serbian_Empire>, which started expanding towards central serbia<Serbia> since the end of the 17th century, while maintaining foothold in modern-day vojvodina<Hungarians_in_Serbia>
abstract.8: in the early 19th century, the serbian<Serbian_language> revolution established the nation-state<Principality_of_Serbia> as the region's first constitutional monarchy, which subsequently expanded its territory
abstract.9: following disastrous casualties in world war i, and the subsequent unification of the habsburg crownland of vojvodina<Hungarians_in_Serbia> with serbia<Serbia>, the country<Serbia> co-founded yugoslavia with other south slavic peoples, which would exist in various political formations until the yugoslav wars of the 1990s
abstract.10: as a result, serbia<Serbia> formed a union with montenegro in 1992, which broke apart in 2006, when serbia<Serbia> again became an independent country<Serbia>
abstract.11: in 2008 the parliament<National_Assembly_of_Serbia> of kosovo<Serbia>, serbia's<Serbia> southern province with an albanian ethnic majority, declared independence, with mixed responses from the international community
abstract.14: the country<Serbia> is acceding to the wto and is a militarily neutral state<Serbia>
